\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 COMPUTATION ITSELF - Manovich pointing out it is inherently spatial, \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8216\'91spatial analogy\u8217\'92 of Donald norman.  "computer technology privileges spatial dimensions" - audio-visual-spatial culture. The role of cybernetics -  its amalgamation of themes of communication and control in computational biological, social, and symbolic systems. Not just space, but environment/ecology. A definition of environment? Environment as system. Vance Byrd review "how spatial metaphors help us imagine how information is organized and how we gain access to it through hypertexts, in "windows," and "cyberspace."" (Tie it to the prototypical qualities from Chapter 2.  For Ryan, digital media is spatial both in how digital media is constructed, how it creates meaning, hgow it represents itsel.(sometimes only metaphorically). "the intricate relationship between games and ecology". Narrative in games is like narrative in painting "not sequence but pure configuration" - no. #3. Computer culture gradually spatialises all representations and experiences - manovich. Manovich - world no longer \u8220\'93petrified\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93mobilised virtual gaze\u8221\'94 - "machines for generating compelling spaces". Koenitz in IDN for chnange talking about the history of calling designers 'architects'. "Space has been a central issue for the study of digital media since the introduction of cyberspace". Calls the ability to act in space in games its "functionality". "the combination of presentation and functionality\u8221\'94 (videogame space book). "Space\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 virtual or real\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 has to be encountered and interacted with". "Through the loophole of virtual space we are able to reclaim the space of the action where we do not \u8220\'93look at\u8221\'94 but actively visit the center of the action." His five types of space in games - rule-based (game system), mediated (what the player experiences), fictional space (imagination), play space (between game and player in real world) and social space (with other humans) - relate to autocosmic interaction with space in life.Need all of them in combination for a game. Talks (17-18) about how games, being simulations on computer, were always about space "Collisions, spatial rela- tions of bodies to each other, audiovisual representations of the environment, interaction with objects in the world and with the world itself\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 all necessarily highlight the spatial qualities of the game." He does not conflate all kinds of digial 'space' (for example, hypertext) - he is talking about 3D games. Hypertext is much less complex, spatially, than a 3D environment. Calls game makers "space-makers" - "provides experiences through the structure of the virtual world" "As Wertheim argues: \u8220\'93Despite its lack of physicality, cyberspace is a real place. I am there\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 whatever this statement may ultimately turn out to mean\u8221\'94 (2000, 229; italics in original). " Tied to cybernetic. Systemic and environmental are tied up. WHERE IS THE PLACE - Gives an overview of using 'dimensions for structuing information and interaction'.}
