\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 HAS VERY MUCH ARISEN IN COMP-ART (AND HERITAGE) - Ryan 2001 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8216\'91habitable environment\u8217\'92, \u8220\'93Simulated, rule-governed worlds.\u8221\'94 (Turkle p 78), Montfort talks about it in IF, Gazzard 2011 - games are a spatial medium, "complex and imaginative graphic realms". What A+C call \u8216\'91scenes\u8217\'92. Her ariosto piece determines how space is used in games., P83 - game\u8217\'92s obsession with enviro as inherited from cinema\u8217\'92s movile framing/exploration of space. "This is what the medium of videogames is made for: the exploration of carefully designed environments" - disagree with him that the beings are also good and a part of this... only as props to a landscape. Murray - Digital environments are \u8220\'93procedural, participatory, spatial and encyclopedic.\u8221\'94. Manovich - Movement "as a tool of narration and exploration" - Navigables pace not just an interface but a cultural form in its own right (his words) - "space's symbolic... capital" across human history. Havot & Wesp - \u8220\'93virtual world geographies\u8221\'94, The history of interactive fiction, as a genre, is a history of narratives of confinement and imprisonment. [theHouse] (Mary Flanagan) - example of early use of 3D environment with text to explore "a relationship between two people coming apart ina confined space". Like Scottish game about abusive relationship - All Roads (Jon Ingold) - another early example of IF being about a space, using space to tell stories, the spatial relationships between characters (in this case, Venice). Curtain - claustrophobia of a space = calustrophibia of a relationship. Chapter #3 - The Great Fire Of London In Minecraft (Museum Of London) - Off The Map (London) (other heritage examples, from Machidon) - Tony Patrickson's That - player's face is the game area (character as environment). La Maison Sensible - installation that rests, that can react to players. Space as character. }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Typically, videogames create \u8216\'91worlds\u8217\'92, \u8216\'91lands\u8217\'92 or \u8216\'91environments\u8217\'92 for players to explore, traverse, conquer, and even dynamically manipulate and transform\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 (Newman, 2004, p.108). }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Mapmaking a "constructive process" in digital - not describing, but creating (Worlds and Maps) - cartogenetic - the making of maps of places, rather than the mapping of places.  Epidauros Amphitheatre, Boardshead and Rose Theatre. A game environment does a lot of things. It\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8230\'85 1. Constrains and guides player movement through physical properties and ecology 2. Uses player reference to communicate simulation boundaries and affordance 3. Reinforces and shapes player identity 4. Provides narrative context. Arose out of "the spatial narrative that had played a prominent role in European visual culture for centuries" (paintings, etc.). p. 232 - "for centures, a spatialized narrative in which all images appeared simultaneously dominated." Therefore narrative does not have to be linear. Laure points out that fiction does this as well - spatial and temporal, cannot detach the two. (I.e. Proust). Spatial vs. temporal art (a distinction made my Lessing (re. Ryan)) is brought together by the simulatory mode in computation. LEssings idea that temporal = narrative is misplaced. ENvironments are highly narrative, and highly autocosmic. Even in IF (When My Boyfriend Came Back From The War). "navigable space... accomplishes the same effects that before were created by literary and cinematic narrative." - \u8220\'93These players evaluate the realism and the ironic elements of GTA's cities by drawing on their existing knowledge of real American cities and of other media depictions of these places. \u8220\'93 As in chapter 1, we engage with gameworld in many of the same ways that we engage with real world. \u8220\'93the gameworld functions as a meaningful place\u8221\'94 (Miller) Calleja\u8217\'92s \u8216\'91spatial involvement\u8217\'92. Henry Jenkins - "game designers don't simply tell stories: they design worlds and sculpt spaces." "The history of videogames reveals an almost linear trajectory of increasingly rich and integrated ecologies of gameworlds." - "I have compared a playable space that people can enter under the guise of an avatar and transform through their actions with a fictional space, which can only be modified by the creatures of the author and only accessed by the reader's imagination. A complete fusion of game and story should be able to combine both types of experience." " Another channel Wolf explores is \u8220\'93Interactivation\u8221\'94 which is the building and engagement of a world through video, computer, immersive and digital technologies." Calleja paper - "The spatial structures of games have an important influence on the structure of the narrative." Nitsche - 2007 - spatiotemproal (both important) in games. "The argument here is that game spaces evoke narratives because the player is making sense of them in order to engage with them. Through a comprehension of signs and interaction with them, the player generates new meaning. The elements that are implemented in the game world to assist in the comprehension will be called \u8220\'93evocative narrative elements,\u8221\'94 because they do not contain a story themselves but trigger important parts of the narrative process in the player. These processes can lead to the generation of a form of narrative." "Game spaces are approached not as foregrounded spectacles based on visual cues such as perspective and parallax but as presented spaces that are assigned an architectural quality. "  "Narrative is seen as a form of understanding of the events a player causes, triggers, and encounters inside a video gam space. From this vantage point, part I reframes key principles of narratology in the context of video game spaces before discussing quests as space-driven content structures for these narrative elements." " not all games depend or support such a placeness" - "The game world remains spatial but lacks the quality of a place." He applies architectural theories to game space - the crafting of space to have meaning, defined by its use. Can influence use and use can influence space. Games do this. Space gaining symbolic value in architecture (drawing on Norberg-Schulz) Explicitly makes links to Herman's 'storyworld' concept - our cognitive map of a fictive world and its systemic relations which constantly change, and for which narratives are a prompt to map them. Makes point that space is not generated through reading the discourse, space generates the discourse, in games. Herman focuses on narratives generating space, rather than the other way around. "games became able to deploy concrete worlds to the player" - she sees it as moving to in-world activities from abstract actions that accounts for greater popularity of games. Na Pali - they are "world-forgers", "something to be navigated and traversed" and "the construction of space that is also a place". In Na Pali - Game 'environments' are not necessarily the encoded environments - code and assets - but the EXPERIENCED spaces. For her, space = game and place = narrative. \u8220\'93The tensions and unities between space and place lie at the heart of most game narratives.\u8221\'94 - "convincing and compelling places to explore". "In a virtual environment then, the setting should also be aninteractive artifact" - }
