\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1	\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 The ease of spatial immersion leads to the heroic, traversive plot having primacy in game narratives. And 'prototypical epistemics'}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "blight" of "exposition graffiti" - \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93"Informational graffiti" in games has become somewhat of a trope now in game design\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1  ---Last Seed, 18th, 4E 201-\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  The wolf is stupid; it plunges straight into the stream after me. Wolves do not do this. They would freeze to death. But here the wolf-machine has no freezing mechanism, nor has that fear of water been authored. The freezing mechanic is not needed to deliberately and shallowly author believable behaviour. ---Last Seed, 17th, 4E 201-\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  The Radiant AI is easy to interrogate into inadequacy - watching a deer on the shoreline near Riverwood, I started to see the rough edges of its animation, the planar weirdness of its stance, the repetition. I'll try approaching it.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The environment is seen as something fixed, therefore easier to put story into. THis idea that it is EASIER. }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "the appeal of broken worlds" - Points out that gaming tropes "developed... through a process that is valid and important" - it must be engaged with. Must look at why we are obsessed with death, and broken worlds, as a way to allow agency, to overcome technical approaches - When we are not finding the corpses of people, we find the corpses of places\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 - "In time, this self-perpetuating skew becomes a fetish, a fascination, a paraphilia."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Bogost - \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93 the empty ruined world has become too common in games\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1	\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 Disagree with Crawford on \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8216\'91spatial vs social reasoning\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Such works do not simulate personhood directly, or expose it to the unpredictable interactions of the player; instead, such works present storyworlds in which, for narrative reasons, the characterisation is firmly preterite and pre-executed; scenarios in which the aesthetic is one of loneliness, pathos and introspection. The solitary player-character explores the }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 "emptiness of the environment" }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 (Bogost),  performing he paradigmatic, easily-rendered physical and ludic actions and collecting pre-authored and static narrative components which represent the characters as foregone conclusions, with no need for present execution. Instead, the systemic, interactive procedure is dedicated to spatial exploration and manipulation of these objects, rather than a systemic or interactive procedure centred on those characters in a 'live' sense. I will detail this approach in more detail in Chapter 3, when I relay my own approach to computational character; it is perhaps currently the most popular compromise between the systemics of comp-art and the techniques of traditional art, and has been employed from early videogames such as }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 Myst }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 (Perlin)}{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1  }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 to more recent 'interactive experiences' such as }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 Dear Esther}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1  (Pinchbeck) and }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 The Witness}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1  (Blow), and its ready adoption in discourses as disparate as the artgame () and virtual heritage (LaMotta, 2012), belies the abnegation of the potential of computational characterisation that it represents. It is what Calleja calls a }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 "ruins fetish" }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 (2011); a trope which artfully handles the formal issues of character through the employment of }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 "virtual pasts instead of virtual presents" }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 (LaMotta, 2012), but which in its overuse constricts the discourse to a non-computational solution to computational character.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Bogost - \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Rockstar\u8217\'92s continued resistenace to moving beyond the stock affordances\u8230\'85 [of simulating] the physical world to model inner lives\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 NPCs sitting in one place or being destroyed outside of player locale.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Characterization in Absentia - eMILY SHorT - \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93ruins fetish\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Compare to \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8216\'91truth spots\u8217\'92 - }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 Truth-spots - work well (ruins) - \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93a remnant of the struggle between culture and nature, as the once-built bends to the ravages of wild time\u8221\'94. }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93A character is just a tiny element of any game, and in many cases, it is a superfluous element." - this is the start of the problem.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "An interactive character is usually a brittle representation, often teetering at the edge of unreality; architecture is much easier than psychology. Games that do make heavy use of interactive NPCs often run into discomfort when those characters are instrumentalized as gameplay tokens."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "palaces are cheap and kings are expenses", "architecture substitutes for psychology."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93But neither the hero nor the secondary characters are ever as eloquent, as dramatic, or as moving as the landscape itself. Indeed, the characters frequently come close to undoing, through a ropey script and stilted delivery, the epic image that the landscape works so hard to establish and sustain.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 Games designers stick to genres that most invested in world-building and spatial storytelling (Jenkins). }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "the emptiness of the environment becomes essential to its operation".}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Lek\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s worlds are empty as well. About exploring. - Lawrence Lek uses environments to explore social and political issues - haunting music, no characters.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Meredith points out the issue is that there are no actors in these worlds.You are on your own. The worlds have not been inhabited by \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93sentient actors\u8221\'94 - as with Champion, no culture.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Characters in this kind of RPG are often highly stylised and clich\u233\'E9d. As Henry Jenkins has suggested of \u8220\'93spatial stories\u8221\'94 more generally, characters are \u8220\'93stripped down to the bare bones\u8221\'94, taking a back seat to the description or presentation of elaborate worlds (2004, p. 122).\~\u8220\'93}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Tavinor's idea of "props" leads onto "nodes".}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Martin - \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 \~In fact it is not character, which is often under-written, and dialogue, which is often clunky, which most successfully sustain these themes. Rather, it is space and place.\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94}
