\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Racter as exploring a space. Even if not a geographic space-  enacts spatial subroutines. "Traditionally, existents are divided into characters and settings based on their significance for the plot" - #3}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "Consequently, in computer games the distinction between static settings and dynamic characters transforms into a more complex continuum of combinations, alterations, and middle terms, because the distribution of static and dynamic game elements doesn't have to mimic any practices in other modes of expression and communication." - the environment can be dynamic as well.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Cheng creating interlapping characterised systems.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 His point that games are external, and stories are internal. Do they have to be. (Koster?) - Get rid of this idea of \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8216\'91interior\u8217\'92 and \u8216\'91exterior\u8217\'92 of a character- just the \u8216\'91systems\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 For what it is,\~}{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Andromeda}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \~was brilliant pulpy fun. But it seems to be the latest in a line of recent games that struggle to give meaning to the vastness of their open spaces.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 a "return to the biologically informed style of cybernetics".}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Distributed AI and Multi-Agent Systems}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Playing With The Past - Talks about "virtual travel" - passing through and interacting with long-gone spaces.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 I am interested in these because they represent something ecosystemic.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Not all DAI and MAS are 'colony architectures' - forming an individual from distinct parts. But certainly DAI is about forming a 'loose entity' - something we can talk about at a macro level. A 'system'.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Multi-Agent Systems is about using multiple simple agents to solve complex problems, agent-based models is about how lots of agents work together, and DAI is really what I am talking about. }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Interesting question - where is the split between agents, and environment? THere is a split WITHIN THE MODEL in MAS, but the environment is BEYOND the system model in DAI.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Similar to actor-network theory - everything can be an agent. A functionally animist view.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Where the individual/entity lies is tied to emergence - where is the 'emergent entity'?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Decentralized individual - remember, MB is not decentralised completely. Not fully or 'embarrassingly' parallel.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Modular, object-oriented: what other words does Bryson draw on for BOD?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 So I am applying a narrative, thematic and philosophical overlay to an engineering approach}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Manifesting self-organisation}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Add 'to-read' for conclusion - colony architectures, individuals as systems, subsumption architeture.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 We could say that the character (the environmental character) in a DAI/MAS system is 'the environment' that the agents change and are part of.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 A 'bottom-up' approach}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 " For example, the more \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8216\'91inhabited\u8217\'92 or \u8216\'91interactive\u8217\'92 environments were not considered more interesting or more \u8216\'91Mayan\u8217\'92. This suggests that Cultural Presence is not}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 synonymous with Social Presence and that cultural learning is too hybrid in nature to be broken down into three distinct modes and tested."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 For 3.4/Conclusion - coherency is HARD.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 In opposition to top-down, GOFAI.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 I'm interested in distributed, behaviour-led - but behaviours can be internal as well.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Subsumption architecture is really at the heart of it, here - a distributed intelligence model. The heart of 'character-as-environment'. But can't solve intelligence problems, all behaviour-based - char-as-enviro is a philosophical way out of this by reconsidering what a character should be, so that we can continue using and refining behaviour-based models.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Have to be less interested in the engineering side.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 SOAR as another DAI approach.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 For conclusion - look at other AI models and see how they affect it. It is more cognitive than behavioural.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Soar is modular, but modules include memory, decision-making, }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 I've slightly fudged and extended BOD to include soar-like elements, but nowhere near as refined or complex. }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Soar is still about building functional AI rather than strict cognitive modelling.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 If we see cognition as a behaviour, happening internally, which we can create competences for, then this would be a good bet - does Bryson want to do this?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 MAS is used for COMPONENTS of naturalistic AI (beliefs, desires, intentions, reinforcement learning) - are functional, engineering approaches}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "social agency (via scripted agents) needs to be very believable in order to evoke a sense of presence. My interpretation of the findings is that while agents can act as powerful navigation cues, if they are not believable then they are ignored." - he is still focussing on the environment!}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 He divides cultural and social - not always the same, cultural is harder to achieve. A cultural understanding of place. Against multiplayer, then! Social presence (being with other people) does not necessarily help us with understanding the culture of the place we are visiting. Cultural presence in place is a form of situated resonance. Here, the social and the cultural come together. (in character-as-environment)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The game that treats body as place/landscape.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Susan Bredlau - the body as place - "loci of intimacy and particularity"}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 So, BOD/SOAR etc. are using FUNCTIONAL METAPHORS of an individual agent/entity as a series of interrelated modules/objects, interacting systematically to emergently produce higher-level behaviour. Char-as-enviro is an AUTOCOSMIC approach to using these functional metaphors within a philosophical/narrative framework. To look for examples, from other real/fictive disciplines, of personhood working in this way, and applying to how we build BOD-esque agents computationally.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The trad-IF world model is terrific at doors and containers, but few interesting stories are actually about the doors and containers themselves. This is just the easiest proxy we have for the idea of gradual discovery.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Attention on a place like attention on a person.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Place is constructed by human perspective - the role of the autocosmic in landscape. The world as constructed by perspective.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Kant's dynamic sublime (a scene that can hurt us that we observe from a distance) and mathematical sublime (the true form for Kant) - the complexity of something beyond the human scale. Conflate interior and exterior, macro and micro.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Remember, cybernetic doesn't just mean system - it means interaction between machine and man. Talk about this more in last section. Cybernetics of approaching environment.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 the 'intentional stance' of Daniel Dennett is invoked frequently (Pinchbeck, Mateas, Lankoski) - mention it right at the end.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Combining theoretical ideas (interdisciplinary) with practical, methodological concerns. }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1\cb2\highlight2 Environmental humanities and related fields as an inspiration - \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 \~this ecology is fatally biased to the modern human individual, and human separated from, and \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93above\u8221\'94 in political and ethical terms, nature.\~\u8220\'93}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "With environmental presence the individual affects and is affected by the outside world. If there is social presence we affect others in a virtual world. If there is cultural presence we should be able to detect a distinctly situated sense of inhabitation, of social values and behaviors preserved and transmitted through ritual, artefact and inscription." Running these three together.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The verticality and interiority of Dear Esther becoming the importance of the memories. Like a \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93ruined memory palace\u8221\'94, a place with which you are interacting, a mind with which you are interacting. \u8220\'93 a projection of the narrator\u8217\'92s trauma onto a landscape\u8221\'94.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 What gets included under the rubric of character is also up for debate, with philosophers, alongside literary scholars, reflecting on the extent to which nonhuman actors\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 for example, the lively objects and animated artifacts that populate works of fiction\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 can be classified as such. }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Increase our idea of personhood.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Says that walking simulators dislodge and complicate the human perspective. - more like nature writing. (haptic landscapes)}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 A character as an environment as an autocosmic approach - instead of trying to build a non-actual person in the traditional sense, take the lessons of enviroment-building (which, as we see above, we are really good at) and apply them to the creation of character - as a place we can get to know, and a person we can explore. As we have seen, we have been interacting with environment as person for millennia. Better-laid foundations, and can use our personalised, characterised reaction to place and environment to build a character-as-environment. Also mix in some of this systemic stuff.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 This approach is all about putting the social into the physical/environmental. }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Katherine cross - cities "come to life and become characters in their own right" - give the players "a means of interacting with the place without violence" - Needs to be more than a "photograph"}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The idea of now doing this deliberately.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Crawford states that }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8216\'91spatial reasoning\u8217\'92 }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 is a }{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8216\'91creative dead-end\u8217\'92}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 , and that we need to move towards creating resonant characters as components within an environment; the traditional approach. }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Koster talking about \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93ecosystems\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93depths\u8221\'94 we need for character.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls9\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Re. Bogost - I definitely don't agree that the pleasure of games is in participating in systems larger than ourselves. Yes, sometimes, but not exclusively. In systems precisely as large as we are. (Finish with this)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Shawn Graham's IF NPC- " Jason Dyer recommended breaking up the Major\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s speeches, for, \u8220\'93the sense of discovery in conversation (in this sort of game) needs to be the same as the sense of discovery in exploring an environment.\u8221\'94"}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Hannah Nicklin, Heartwood Interview - \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1\cb2\highlight2 place-as-character\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Relate Actor-network theory to the idea of characters as nodes - reduce their importance in a system - become a flat hierarchy of mediators. change the focus - zoom out a bit . Adding a metaphor on top of object-oriented programming to see if it works well - beyond just pure theoretical/structural to semiotic - the meaning of environments as characterful, agentful systems.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "blurs the boundary between subjectivity and materiality, agency and passivity".}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "an ancient extension of this wild place, disturbed by my presence" -"The colossi often look like long-abandoned temples come to life".}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1	\loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f3\fs22\b0\i1\cf1 Everything - Alan Watts philosophy - }{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 An experiment in personhood - in what a character should be. \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Tremendous connectedness of everything\u8221\'94 About the systematics of life and existence.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The intricacies of character relations are sacrificed to the broader, and far less granular, movements of space.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Newman - players relate to the whole gameworld simultaneously - the character of mario is part of the world that they inhabit (remember you spoke against this in chapter 1) - his idea that the character is bound up in the world.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Not taking a formalist point of view - not interested in 'character as function' (Propp, in Caraciolo) - as caraciolo states, somewhere between functionalist and mimetic, disregarding the totality of both - an 'econarratology of character'. I don't want to decouple character, remember (Chapter 1), but still interested in 'agencies' (Chapter 2), but still want to stay 'perdurant'.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Broadly speaking, narrative tends to place human characters in the agentive position, while nonhuman realities (including nonhuman animals and natural landscapes or processes) are relegated to the position of objects: tools to further human ends, or a backdrop to human-centered events.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 'it' having no subject, but representing an ambient process. (like Anne does with creature)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 It comes down to 'what can be a person'?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "promotion of a place to subject"}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 character-as-environment is econarratological theory of character.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 " The thrust of the econarratological theory of character I have started to outline in this article is that narrative, and particularly fictional narrative, has the capacity to probe modes of causal efficacy that are alternative to human agency and subjectivity."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Instrumentalism of ritual can be used.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 I disagree with her that aesthetic stimuli are always taken as trying to communicate something, as symbolic, whereas other stimuli are not - they mixed a lot in the deep past. What is aesthetic.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Ties with Mar's point about inferring the authors goals by what is included in the narrative and mixing with our own goals for reading the narrative. (2004)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 How can we understand the mind of an actant like environment (drawing on Palmer(Palmer's 'intermental' or 'social' mind - the collective minds of towns, couples, groups of people - beyond the single human. ('Distributed cognition' - inspired by ant hives. Ryan's review of Palmer's work provides an introduction to this.) - Ryan disagrees that places can be agents - a collective mind is different from a singular mind. But I think its a case of frames. While Ryan states (and Palmer agrees) that individual and social minds are different, I believe that the latter can be used to produce a sort of the former through metaphor.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Calling them 'virtual humans' in machidon et al. Not human?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 For lowering the scope - "a single virtual human not only mimics a real guide (which in the real world is also usually a single person) but also significantly reduces the complexity of the implementation." (machidon)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Focalisation too big normally.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "We have found that interaction within First-Person Walkers is not so much navigation within the game world, but an investigation motivated by intrigue and speculation."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Wolf\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s \u8216\'91gestalt\u8217\'92}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "A different kind of mistake is found in some commercial approaches to virtual worlds. Here, space in video games serves too often as polygon-rich spectacle and \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93eye candy\u8221\'94 that remains largely unused in the actual gameplay. It is time to revise this immature misconception and build new connections along the way for further debate."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 "However, my friend\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s connection to the character went far beyond}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 a replaceable game token\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 it grew out of the cognitive work invested into}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 the game."}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The arhiteture of personhood. A good phrase.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 Na Pali is the star of the game, in a way - the main thing you are fighting with/against. You are just "trying to save your own ass" from the environment.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs22\b0\i0\cf1 The ritualistic element of game environments - changing to accomodate your personal growth - is baked into them. Their response to the player is part of them. They are not 'unresponsive' or 'unpersonalised' like real environments - they are actually built to respond to you - like characters are. Na Pali is character-as-environment: it is a lone character traversing a world as a metaphor for escape, discovery, wonder. Of interacting with a 'total entity' - Na Pali, rather than any one character.}
